2vr.title: Modus tollens
2vr.clickbait: Deriving a negation from another negation
2vr.text:
We also can work with negations to create a valid argument:

>  $ \begin{array}{l}
\text{If Socrates is a fish, then Socrates can live underwater.}  \\
\text{Socrates cannot live underwater.} \\\hline
\text{Therefore, Socrates is not a fish.} 
\end{array} $

Also known as *law of contrapositive* or *denying the consequent*, modus tollens works by reversing modus ponens. Formally,

> $ \begin{array}{l}
A \rightarrow B \\
\neg B \\\hline
\therefore \neg A
\end{array} $
